canonical:
  title: 祭閔平章文 代夫人作
  author: 李奎報
  language: lzh
  text: 月日云云嗚呼哀哉文章蘊蓄非妾所窺公之遇主千載一時風雲感會奮鬣揚鬐位極冢宰揔領百司乞身退逸尙十餘朞洪範之五福純備汾陽之終始無虧大期莫逭今也安之於公無憾生者之悲婦人所有唯是涕洟送不得越門去不得執紼不知何山之趾何兆何穴埋爾玉樹沉光永滅嗚呼哀哉猶有二子雙飛天路妾有所依幸勿爲顧妾亦老矣生復幾何酌酒以侑已矣嗟嗟
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 祭閔平章文 代夫人作
  author: 李奎報
  language: lzh
  text: 月日云云。嗚呼哀哉。文章蘊蓄。非妾所窺。公之遇主。千載一時。風雲感會。奮鬣揚鬐。位極冢宰。揔領百司。乞身退逸。尙十餘朞。洪範之五福純備。汾陽之終始無虧。大期莫逭。今也安之。於公無憾。生者之悲。婦人所有。唯是涕洟。送不得越門。去不得執紼。不知何山之趾何兆何穴。埋爾玉樹。沉光永滅。嗚呼哀哉。猶有二子。雙飛天路。妾有所依。幸勿爲顧。妾亦老矣。生復幾何。酌酒以侑。已矣嗟嗟。
korean:
  title: 민평장에게 제사 지내는 글 부인 대신 짓다
  author: 이규보
  language: kor
  text: 모월 모일. 아, 슬프다. 문장을 많이 쌓아 놓은 것은 첩의 엿볼 바가 아니로다. 공이 임금을 만난 것은 천재일우인지라, 풍운이 서로 만나 말이 갈기를 떨치는 듯 벼슬길에 올라 지위가 정승이 되어서 백관을 총괄하였고, 그 후 몸을 빌어 물러나온 지가 10년이 넘었도다. 홍범(洪範)의 오복(五福)이 다 갖추었고 분양(汾陽)의 시종(始終)은 어지러짐이 없었도다. 대기(大期 죽는 기한)를 면하지 못하고 지금 와서 어디에 갔는가요. 공은 유감이 없지만 산 사람이 슬프니, 나에겐 오직 눈물뿐이로다. 보낼 때 문밖에도 나가 보지 못하고 떠나갈 때 상여줄을 잡아보지도 못하였으니, 알지 못하겠소. 어느 산기슭 어느 터 어느 혈(穴)에 당신 같은 옥수(玉樹)를 묻어서 그 빛을 길이 멸해 버리는지. 아, 슬프다. 그래도 두 아들이 있어서 조정[天路]에 쌍쌍이 나가고 있으니 첩은 의지할 곳이 있은지라, 돌아보지 말고 가시오. 첩도 이제 늙었으니 산들 다시 얼마나 살겠소. 술을 쳐서 권하오니 모든 것이 끝났도다. 아, 슬프다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_1120_010_0160&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: 'A Eulogy for Minister Min: Composed on Behalf of His Wife'
  author: Lee Gyeou-bo
  language: eng
  text: 'On this day of days—oh, what sorrow. The wealth of scholarship and refinement lies beyond what this concubine could ever comprehend. Your encounter with our sovereign was a meeting of heaven and earth that comes but once in a thousand years. Like wind and cloud converging, like a steed tossing its mane in triumph, you rose to the highest office—Chancellor of State, overseeing all the ministries. Then, after more than a decade of rest in retirement, you gathered all the Five Blessings spoken of in the sacred texts, your life complete and unblemished as that of the great ministers of old. The great span of years could not be evaded. Now you have gone—and while you depart without regret, we who remain can only grieve. For this woman, there is nothing but tears. I could not follow you beyond the gates; I could not grasp the ceremonial rope as you departed. I know not which mountain, which auspicious site, which sacred earth holds your precious form—that jade tree whose radiance is now extinguished forever. Oh, what sorrow. Yet comfort remains: two sons still soar in service to the throne, so this old wife has something upon which to lean. Do not turn back to look upon me. I too grow old—how many days remain? I offer this cup of wine in your honor, and with it, all is ended. Ah, such grief.'
  footnotes:
    - The 'Five Blessings' (五福) are a classical Chinese concept representing longevity, wealth, health, virtue, and a peaceful death.
    - The reference to 'Fenyang' (汾陽) alludes to Guo Zixin, a celebrated Tang general who served with distinction and retired without scandal—a model of perfect service and virtue.
    - The 'Jade Tree' is a metaphor for a person of exceptional beauty and worth, here referring to the deceased minister.
    - The 'Heavenly Path' (天路) refers to service in the imperial court and government.
